\begin_layout Standard
The closed formulas of exponential sums associated with the elementary symmetric
 polynomial defined over field of galois are the central axis in the research
 presented in chapter 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

.
 It is well known in many areas of the mathematics that the tool of discrete
 fourier transform is a mathematical object used for fast and efficient
 calculations.
 In this thesis, chapter 3, presents how to obtain a characteristic polynomial
 of a linear recurrence homogeneous of exponential sums of symmetric polynomials
 defined over Galois field.
 In the same way as shown, in the equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:9"

\end_inset

), Boolean case.
 For example, the theorem 
\begin_inset Formula $3.1$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "cm1"

\end_inset

 is a general Boolean version of result of Cai, Green, and Thierauf.
 Similar to equation 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\ref{eq:9}\right)$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq k_{1}<\cdots<k_{s}$
\end_inset

 be fixed integers and 
\begin_inset Formula $r=\lfloor\log_{2}(k_{s})\rfloor+1$
\end_inset

.
 The value of the exponential sum 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S(\boldsymbol{e}_{n,[k_{1},\cdots,k_{s}]})=S(\boldsymbol{e}_{n,k_{1}})+\cdots+S(\boldsymbol{e}_{n,k_{s}})
\]

\end_inset

 is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
S(\boldsymbol{e}_{n,[k_{1},\cdots,k_{s}]})=c_{0}2^{n}+\sum_{j=1}^{2^{r}-1}c_{j}\lambda_{j}^{n},\label{eq:1.3.1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{j}=1+\zeta_{j}$
\end_inset

 , 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta_{j}=e^{\frac{\pi i\,j}{2^{r-1}}},\,\,i=\sqrt{-1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{j}$
\end_inset

 are constant elements.
 The formula 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:1.3.1"

\end_inset

 is a closed formula for exponential sum 
\begin_inset Formula $S(\boldsymbol{e}_{n,[k_{1},\cdots,k_{s}]})$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The formula in equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:1.3.1"

\end_inset

) implicitly depends on the discrete fourier transform to reach it (see
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "cai,cm1"

\end_inset

).
 The implementation of these formulas in any mathematics program allows
 the calculation of the value of the exponential sum 
\begin_inset Formula $S(\boldsymbol{e}_{n,[k_{1},\cdots,k_{s}]})$
\end_inset

 to be efficient in any computer.
 Once again, the discrete fourier transform and mathematical object of circulat
 matrices are the basis for obtaining the closed formulas of 
\begin_inset Formula $S(\boldsymbol{e}_{n,k})$
\end_inset

 for any Gaois field (see chapter 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

).
 The closed formula of 
\begin_inset Formula $S(\boldsymbol{e}_{n,k})$
\end_inset

 allows us to show that the sequence 
